{{Refimprove|date=August 2018}}
In medicine the term '''cheesewiring''' or '''cheesewire effect''' describes any process in which [[cells]] or [[intercellular matrix]] are [[dissect]]ed or [[extrusion|extruded]] either by the material being pressed through a taut element, or by the tension of a taut element pulling through tissue.
==As a complication== Cheesewiring can be a complication or part of a negative outcome of a procedure. Examples include tumor growth penetrating the openings in a [[Self-expandable metallic stent|bowel stent]] that was placed to open an [[obstructed bowel]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Vrazas|first1=JI|last2=Ferris|first2=S|last3=Bau|first3=S|last4=Faragher|first4=I|title=Stenting for obstructing colorectal malignancy: an interim or definitive procedure|journal=ANZ Journal of Surgery|date=June 2002|volume=72|issue=6|pages=392–6|doi=10.1046/j.1445-2197.2002.02426.x|pmid=12121155}}</ref> sutures used to hold a transplanted [[cornea]] in place cutting through the cornea,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bartels|first1=MC|last2=van Rooij|first2=J|last3=Geerards|first3=AJ|last4=Mulder|first4=PG|last5=Remeijer|first5=L|title=Comparison of complication rates and postoperative astigmatism between nylon and mersilene sutures for corneal transplants in patients with Fuchs endothelial dystrophy|journal=Cornea|date=June 2006|volume=25|issue=5|pages=533–9|doi=10.1097/01.ico.0000214218.60249.e5|pmid=16783141}}</ref> and treatment of [[tendon rupture]], when sutures pull through the tendon.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Peltz|first1=TS|last2=Haddad|first2=R|last3=Scougall|first3=PJ|last4=Nicklin|first4=S|last5=Gianoutsos|first5=MP|last6=Oliver|first6=R|last7=Walsh|first7=WR|title=Structural Failure Mechanisms of Common Flexor Tendon Repairs|journal=Hand Surgery|date=October 2015|volume=20|issue=3|pages=369–79|doi=10.1142/S0218810415400092|pmid=26387996}}</ref>
==As an intentional procedure== The term can also be used for to name the process of using a guidewire or suture intentionally to cut through tissue during a surgical procedure or allowing a suture to slowly cut through tissue over time.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ullery|first1=BW|last2=Chandra|first2=V|last3=Dake|first3=M|last4=Lee|first4=JT|title=Cheese wire fenestration of a chronic juxtarenal dissection flap to facilitate proximal neck fixation during EVAR|journal=Annals of Vascular Surgery|date=January 2015|volume=29|issue=1|pages=124.e1–5|doi=10.1016/j.avsg.2014.07.025|pmid=25192823}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tashiro|first1=J|last2=Baqai|first2=A|last3=Goldstein|first3=LJ|last4=Salsamendi|first4=JT|last5=Taubman|first5=M|last6=Rey|first6=J|title="Cheese wire" fenestration of a chronic aortic dissection flap for endovascular repair of a contained aneurysm rupture|journal=Journal of Vascular Surgery|date=August 2014|volume=60|issue=2|pages=497–9|doi=10.1016/j.jvs.2013.06.066|pmid=23911248}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Prem-Venkatesh|last2=Ramamurthi|first2=S|last3=Montgomery|first3=DM|title=The use of a "cheese-wire" suture in trabeculectomy|journal=The British Journal of Ophthalmology|date=April 2007|volume=91|issue=4|pages=500–4|pmid=17372339|pmc=1994764|doi=10.1136/bjo.2006.100057}}</ref> Treatment of [[fistula]]s often involves placing a suture and allowing it to cut off the fistula over time.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moses|first1=RA|last2=Ann Gormley|first2=E|title=State of the Art for Treatment of Vesicovaginal Fistula|journal=Current Urology Reports|date=August 2017|volume=18|issue=8|pages=60|pmid=28656520|doi=10.1007/s11934-017-0708-5}}</ref>
